<h2>Common LG Dryer Problems We Fix Daily</h2>
<p>LG dryers have predictable failure patterns that our technicians encounter regularly. Thermal fuses blow when lint accumulates in the exhaust system — don't try to replace one yourself because one wrong connection creates a fire hazard. Door latches fail on older DLEX models, usually after three to four years of daily use. The plastic striker wears down and won't engage the safety switch properly. Heating elements burn out gradually, so you'll notice clothes taking longer to dry before they stop heating completely. Control boards can fail due to power surges, especially during summer months when the electrical grid gets stressed. We also see moisture sensors go bad on high-end Signature models, causing the dryer to either over-dry or shut off too early. Most of these repairs take under two hours when you've got the right part and know exactly where to look.</p>
<h3>Drum Not Turning Issues</h3>
<p>Usually the belt or drive motor. Our techs can tell which one by the sound pattern when you try to start a cycle.</p>
<h3>No Heat Problems</h3>
<p>Could be the heating element, gas valve solenoids, or high-limit thermostat. We test each component systematically.</p>
